hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Start with the formula:
   $$b_0 = \frac{11}{3}\,C_2(G) \;-\;\frac{1}{3}\sum_{k=1}^{N_s}T(R_k).$$

2. For SU(3), $C_2(G)=3$ and there is one scalar ($N_s=1$) in the rank-2 symmetric representation. 

3. The index of the rank-2 symmetric representation is
   $$T(R)=\frac{N+2}{2} \quad\text{with }N=3 \;\Longrightarrow\; T(R)=\frac{5}{2}.$$

4. Substitute into $b_0$:
   $$b_0 = \frac{11}{3}\cdot 3 \;-\;\frac{1}{3}\,\frac{5}{2}
          = 11 \;-\;\frac{5}{6}
          = \frac{66}{6} \;-\;\frac{5}{6}
          = \frac{61}{6}.$$
